ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[This is extremely sad for the horses as well as for all involved. While these horses likely had little immunity to the diseases, crowding and stressing and poor sanitary conditions did not improve the overall situation.

The cost per day is high, and one has to ask why are they not put on federal land? Are there no facilities? Is it not equipped for horses or for human caretakers?

Respiratory diseases will move more quickly through stressed and crowded animals. When the horses are rounded up, they are usually crowded, as it prevents attempts by the horses to jump out, possibly injuring themselves further. However, crowding and stressing when there is a disease, is largely a prescription for disasters such as we are witnessing.

It is sad, as well as surprising, to learn how infrequent the pen areas were being cleaned. Keeping the animals in filthy conditions only contributes to stress and disease spread. - Mod.TG

ProMED map of Colorado, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8702988,209]
